Fabulous food that's worth the price. Love their teriyaki beef! I could eat there every night. Always prompt with take-out and delivery. Can't speak more highly of this place.

Sushi is pretty good but it seems the great customer service I read about in former reviews has not survived covid. I’ve ordered twice for pick-up and both times when I arrived (food supposed to be ready) they unapologetically told me it was not ready yet. When I explain the Menufy email gave me a time and it was supposed to be ready, literally no response. Just looked at me. Over 15 minutes late for a sushi order that was supposed to be ready in 40 minutes, which is a bit long for a sushi order anyway.

Can’t believe it took a pandemic for me to try this place. Always excellent sushi. We’ve done both take out and delivery and it really holds up well. The owners are really nice too. Particularly fond of their shimmy vegetable tempura and spicy tuna roll.

I visited this place nearly a year ago, and yet it is the one restaurant that I remember as being my favorite to experience when visiting Chicago. Ate here 3 times that week! Awesome staff, top-knotch food, homey atmosphere. Very memorable place!

What a gem. Great food and service. The tofu appetizer is a great start to a delicious lunch. The shoyu ramen and e combination as pictured. Plenty of street parking.

We frequently order delivery from Matsuya, but with some friends from out of town visiting we went tonight to dine in. All in our party loved the food (incl. my 2yo, who ate several pieces of teriyaki chicken, half a bowl of rice, and half a piece of maki). And service was just perfect, there when we needed them and not when we were socializing. And they were very kind to my 2yo, as well.
Nice, clean, and authentic sushi

Nice staff, arrived  late and super hungry. Ordered tempura, chicken katsu and sashimi. Nice portions size.  Update: went back more times and tried both the salmon teriyaki and the pork katsu. The salmon as you can see in the picture was very dry and pretty much tasteless. The pork was also very tough to eat. Now the sashimi It was always good, no complaints as well as the tempura. Maybe the rolls are better but then I don’t eat too much rice.

The food was absolutely wonderful! The staff made sure to check on us frequently and took great care of the group I was with. The atmosphere was bright but calm, and the next time I visit Chicago I will be stopping by again!!
Remember the original down the street but quality at this new location is pretty spot on. NOT AS MANY SELECTIONS AS THE OLDER ONE ☝️ BUT STIIL OK

This was Shiroi Hana for decades and hadnt realized they changed hands.  Superb.  Two types of toro on the menu and the cuts of sashimi toro i had was the size of a petite filet mignon. Thick beautiful cuts of toro at a reasonable price. Hard to find toro on typical sushi joint menus these days.  Even more impressive was the Sukiyaki. Again, rare on a menu these days as Ramen is all the rage. We also had a whole rainbow trout that was delicate and flaky and done to perfection.  Oyster shooters with fresh quail egss and the other sashimi was excellent.  Highly reccomend this *real* Japanese restaurant.
Fresh and better than usual fish selections.  Aji whole fish sashimi is a must try.

This restaurant was absolutely horrific in every way. If possible, I would give this restaurant less than 1 star. The only thing worse than that the food was the service. We sent back almost every dish that was given to us and nobody apologized to us or asked if we wanted anything else. Our waitress disappeared after bringing our waters and we were never given more water nor were we brought silverware or extra plates unless we got up and asked. The staff was speechless when we brought all these problems to their attention. Please if you’re thinking about eating at this restaurant go as far away from here as you can.

We had a party of six, and asked how long is the wait. They said "10-15 minutes, we will combine 2 tables for your group" Ok, so we parked the car and fed the meter. Once we got there, the mean fat girl(only way to discribe her)said we can't accommodate you, because we can't combine the 2 tables. Why didnt you tell us earlier and not after we paid $5 for the meter??? Never will we eat or recommend this restaurant. Fat girl has issues. Sorry, but that's the truth.

Well made authentic Japanese food. Good selection of sushi, sashimi and many common hot dishes. I had the unadon (eel dish) and some tuna nigiri. Everything was super tasty and the tuna melted in your mouth.

A very cozy, friendly restaurant. They have fairly standard sushi options with a few things that are a little more unusual. The special when we visited was monkfish livers for example. The sushi was well-prepared and seemed very fresh. We'll definitely be returning.

Among the best in Chicago, without pretence. Has been in business for quite a while, with a short break when they lost their location nearer Wrigley Field and moved to the present spot. The sushi and cooked Japanese food is superb. 6 seat bar and tables. Selection of higher end sake and Japanese beers.

Friendly staff and fast sevice. Very fresh sushi, my favorite is the Dynamite appetizer and their Uni( sea urchin) very generous on the uni unlike other resturants ive been too. Definitely recommend it!

Matsuya is perfect. Not too small, or big, wonderful menu, the miami tempura roll is orgasmic, and the combination c fits so well in my budget. Only thing is parking. They don't have their own parking lot and this is in a busy neighborhood.

I don't understand why everyone is making such a big deal of a Japanese head chef here, that man you speak of is the owner he gets behind the sushi bar when he wants to, the chef cooking the hot meals in the back are a mexican man and woman who do a great job And the "head chef" is the big friendly mexican guy who has been the owner's  pride and joy since as long as I can remember. The entire prep and cook staff has been there through 2 previous owners so what does that tell you¿ they made Matsuya what it is today

Love Matsuya!  The chef is a true artist and a master.  The hot food here is great, some great traditional items Takoyaki for example is fantastic.  the sushi is beautiful and fresh.  this place is bumping with people on dates on the weekends and there's some delicious sake for those you who care to imbibe.  Overall a great sushi place with reasonable prices.  not all souped up like some of the lincoln park places, this is traditional and simple. Fantastic!

I had the sashimi with a Godzilla roll. I'm typically a very heavy critic, but this food was absolutely stunning not just in presentation but taste. They even had flowers on the sushi and the wasabi was very high in quality! I cannot believe I only found this place recently. Would recommend!

I had sushi and ramen soup. Service was very good; it was provided with a smile and my drink was never empty. The ramen was perfect with a chewy texture. The broth was good to the last drop. The vinegar rice could have been more perky but the sashimi was very fresh. Highly recommended.

Finally, a Japanese chef! Very friendly service, probably because we eat here about once a week. We often get small plates compliments of the chef and very much enjoy the atmosphere here. They offer a full selection of tradition Japanese meals. I have always gotten exactly what I was craving. You won't be disappointed!
Impressive that finally I can found the place with a Japanese chef in Japanese restaurant. Great kitchen items, fresh sushi and sashimi.

If I had to guess, Matsuya has been a neighborhood spot for many years.  On a recent first visit, I opted to sit at the sushi bar to get to know the place.  The head sushi chef is probably the man in charge of the place.  He's a super friendly man who clearly enjoys what he does.  Places like this make me happy and I wish that more restaurants brought personality to the table.  As a bit of a snob when it comes to my sushi, I have to say that Matsuya does what it does well concerning flavors and playing them off one of another in a roll or plated preparation of fish.  I'm a bit of a traditionalist and find that the cuts of fish used for sashimi, while very fresh, are a bit large and do not allow for a complete savoring of the supposed to be one bite.  The preparations are done with care and don't try to stretch any further than they need to be to be appealing to the eye.  I typically order a chirashi from a legit sushi house to determine the freshness of fish and skill of the chef.  The chef is very skilled but has probably bent to bring what people perceive as more value when eating at a sushi restaurant.  If in the area, I'd love to give more of my business to Matsuya.
No more all you can eat sushi.  But it still is BYOB.
all you can eat sushi under $20 how can you beat that deal. The service is great. the food is great what else can you ask for!
